ce:section.ce:para:
The adsorption of PA on the surface of AlP-NS (see Fig. 1
                        ) was explored by selecting a model of AlP-NS (Al103P103H39). H atoms were used for the saturation of its end atoms. The Al-P bond had an average bond length of approximately 2.31 Å. Based on the DOS diagram in Fig. 1, the energy of the LUMO level was −3.807 and that of the HOMO was −6.425 eV for AlP-NS (see Table 1
                        ). Therefore, the estimated Eg was about 2.618 eV. At M06-2X, Eg was approximately 2.679 eV and it was roughly 2.613 eV at B97D. As shown in Fig. 2
                        , PA has some functional groups on a hexagonal ring. There was a HOMO profile (O atoms) in the structure of PA, which was a suitable site to attack the Al atoms of AlP-NS (see Fig. 2).

As shown in Table 2, the electronic properties of Sc@AlP-NS significantly changed following the adsorption of PA. A change was observed in the HOMO of Sc@AlP-NS from −5.649 to −5.352 eV. So, there was a reduction in Eg from 1.847 to 1.553 eV. In CMP PA/Sc@AlP-NS, as shown in the partial DOS diagram, a new occupied state appeared at −5.352 eV following the adsorption of PA onto the Sc@AlP-NS (see Fig. 6
                        ). That is to say, a change was observed in the HOMO level of the Sc@AlP-NS to −5.352 eV. As illustrated in Fig. 7
                        , PA contributed to the formation of this state. Furthermore, the HOMO of CMP shifted considerably on PA, thereby leading to a dramatic change in its energy. Such a dramatic change in the electronic properties, high CT and more negative adsorption energies confirmed that the adsorption capacity was enhanced.
